I can&#39;t tell you why &quot;code chef&quot; is not accepting it because I don&#39;t know this site so I don&#39;t know how it compiles code, **but** I can tell you why your code is wrong in general when I compile it on a regular IDE, which is a more usefult information, trust me. I suggest you to write these exercises on an IDE (like I did), because in this case your original solution didn&#39;t compile at all.

Here the problems with your code:

 - The method is `Scanner.nextInt()`, not `Scanner.next_Int()`;
 - There were several lines not properly commented;
 - You printed the right and the porpousely wrong solution without separating them, so it is possible the chef readed it as a single number. Replace `System.out.print` with `System.out.println`
 - [About the try-catch][1]...
  - You don&#39;t need to declare your main method is throwing java.lang.Exception;
  - Never catch a generic superclass java.lang.Exception. Just, never.
  - If you catch an Exception never leave the catch body empty. It&#39;s pointless.
  - The combination &quot;catch Exception + empty catch body&quot; is possibly the worst thing one can do in Java. It just stops your code anytime for any reason with no chance for you to debug it.
 - Not an error, but the whole &quot;scan and if&quot; part can be replaced by the single line:
`int c = Math.abs(scan.nextInt() - scan.nextInt())`
You don&#39;t need `a` and `b` anymore after the calculation, and you can just &quot;remove the minus sign&quot; with the absolute value.


Anyway, here it is how I would solve the problem, with an algorithm that can generate one of every acceptable answers. *(With this I mean that technically to satisfy the request you could always &quot;cheese it&quot;, for instance by always changing the last one.)*
````
public static void main (String[] args)
{
	Scanner scan = new Scanner(System.in);
	int c = Math.abs(scan.nextInt() - scan.nextInt());      //get sign-less difference
	System.out.println(c);
  
	ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; digits = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();          //creating a list for the digits
	for (int i=c; i&gt;0; i/=10){
		digits.add(i%10);                                   //adding a digit to the list
	}

	int randomIndex = (int) (Math.random()*digits.size());            //picking a random digit index
	int randomDigit = digits.get(randomIndex), newDigit;
	do {
		newDigit = (int) (Math.random()*10);                        //Randomize a new digit
	} while ( newDigit == randomDigit || (randomIndex==0 &amp;&amp; randomDigit==0));   //Repeat if it is the same OR if it both the first one and it is 0
	digits.set(randomIndex, newDigit);      						//update the list
	int answer = 0;
	for (int i = 0 ; i &lt; digits.size(); i++ ){
		answer += digits.get(i).intValue() * Math.pow(10,i);        //Revert the list into a integer
	}

	System.out.println(answer);
}
````

Hope I helped!


