Laravel has a [subdomain][1] support in routing out of the box. From the official documentation, 

    Route::domain(&#39;{account}.myapp.com&#39;)-&gt;group(function () {
        Route::get(&#39;user/{id}&#39;, function ($account, $id) {
            //
        });
    });
The account portion is not hardcoded. It is dynamic. So you can put various logic inside it. For example, if I want to access `ryan.example.com` then you will need to check whether I am really Ryan or not. You can also use middleware like you can use for other routes.

Also check that you can use $account variable in functions. If you wish then you can use that $account to get &quot;user id or other user details from that url segment.&quot;

I hope this answer will be enough to get you started. If you get stuck somewhere then share with us again with any specific problem and we will try to help you. 

  [1]: https://laravel.com/docs/5.8/routing#route-group-sub-domain-routing

