The Builder-pattern is useful when you have multiple parameters that are exchangeable (and optional). Then you can just chain them together and configure your object. But in the end they only initialize an object. So if you have say 20 parameters and your object needs always the same 10 alone to function, then putting this in the builder pattern isn&#39;t worth your while. 


Let&#39;s say this is the obgligatory minimum:

    new CalculInteretsParPeriodeBuilder()
            .withEncours(10000)
            .withTauxWithMarge(1.0)
            .withDtEch(DateCalculs.getDate(2019, Month.FEBRUARY, 1))
            .withDtEchPrec(DateCalculs.getDate(2018, Month.FEBRUARY, 1))
            .withIsFirstEcheanceInterets(false);

 
Then just calling a constructor is shorter:

    CalculInteretsParameters params = new CalculInteretsParameters(
            10000,
            1.0,
            DateCalculs.getDate(2019, Month.FEBRUARY, 1),
            DateCalculs.getDate(2018, Month.FEBRUARY, 1),
            false
    );
 
And in my opinion there is nothing wrong with some simple `setter` calls for all the optional parameters:


     params.setPeriodiciteI(Periode.ANNUELLE);
     params.setPeriodiciteK(Periode.ANNUELLE);

     if(reallyNecessary){           // see? way more dynamic :)
         params.setTauxNDecimal(2);
         params.setPeriodeCalculInterets(PeriodeCalculInterets.PAR_PERIODE);
     }else{
         params.setBaseCalcul(BaseCalcul.BC_360360);
     }
            
In your case I wouldn&#39;t use it. Just initialize a parameter object (as dynamic as you want and need it to) and pass it to the calculation method.


**EDIT**

Sorry, to actually answer your question I would go with a parameter class:

     CalculInteretsParameters params = new CalculInteretsParameters();
     params.setTauxWithMarge(1.0);  //  set all your dates, numbers and parameters
     params.setPeriodicite(2);
     ...

     // then call your method (maybe even with some dynamic values)
     calculInteretsParPeriode(params, someDynamicValue);

